Use an accessor/function in both frameworks so the query is rebuilt when inputs change.

Svelte:
```ts
const employees = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  managerId ? app.employees.where({ managerId }) : undefined,
);
```

Solid:
```tsx
const employees = useAll(() => ({
  query: managerId() ? app.employees.where({ managerId: managerId() }) : undefined,
}));
```

Do not prebuild the query outside those accessors.

```ts
import { schema as s } from "jazz-tools";

const schema = {
  employees: s.table({
    name: s.string(),
    managerId: s.ref("employees").optional(),
  }),
};

type AppSchema = s.Schema<typeof schema>;
export const app: s.App<AppSchema> = s.defineApp(schema);
```

`managerId` creates an optional self-reference back to `employees`.

Use the conventional chunked-file tables and let an `uploads` row own access.

```ts
import { schema as s } from "jazz-tools";

const schema = {
  file_parts: s.table({
    data: s.bytes(),
  }),
  files: s.table({
    name: s.string().optional(),
    mimeType: s.string(),
    partIds: s.array(s.ref("file_parts")),
    partSizes: s.array(s.int()),
  }),
  uploads: s.table({
    owner_id: s.string(),
    label: s.string(),
    fileId: s.ref("files"),
  }),
};
```

Permissions should keep `uploads` private to the owner, allow narrow direct inserts on `files` and `file_parts` because helpers create them before the parent exists, then inherit read/delete from the parent chain:

```ts
policy.uploads.allowRead.where({ owner_id: session.user_id });
policy.uploads.allowInsert.where({ owner_id: session.user_id });
policy.uploads.allowUpdate.where({ owner_id: session.user_id });
policy.uploads.allowDelete.where({ owner_id: session.user_id });

policy.files.allowInsert.where({});
policy.file_parts.allowInsert.where({});

policy.files.allowRead.where(allowedTo.readReferencing(policy.uploads, "fileId"));
policy.file_parts.allowRead.where(allowedTo.readReferencing(policy.files, "partIds"));
policy.files.allowDelete.where(allowedTo.deleteReferencing(policy.uploads, "fileId"));
policy.file_parts.allowDelete.where(allowedTo.deleteReferencing(policy.files, "partIds"));
```

Do not rename `files`/`file_parts` or the `mimeType`, `partIds`, `partSizes`, `data` columns if you want the built-in file helpers to work.

Require edge durability on both upload steps, then distinguish missing files from incomplete local chunk data.

```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(app, blob, { tier: "edge" });

const upload = await db
  .insert(app.uploads, {
    owner_id: session.user_id,
    label: "Profile photo",
    fileId: file.id,
  })
  .wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

For download, request the tier you need and handle incomplete chunks explicitly:

```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "edge" });
  return { state: "ready", blob };
} catch (error) {
  if (error.name === "FileNotFoundError") {
    return { state: "missing" };
  }
  if (error.name === "IncompleteFileDataError") {
    return { state: "incomplete", reason: error.reason };
  }
  throw error;
}
```

Use `tier: "edge"` because success means all chunks have reached edge, not merely local storage. Treat `IncompleteFileDataError` as a recoverable product state such as “still downloading” or “data incomplete”, not as a missing file.

Delete in dependency order while inherited permissions still exist: load parent, load file, delete parts, delete file, then delete parent.

```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (!upload) return;

const file = await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) {
    db.delete(app.file_parts, partId);
  }
  db.delete(app.files, file.id);
}

db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id);
```

Do not delete the `uploads` row first. If you do, the inherited delete permissions for `files` and `file_parts` can disappear before cleanup finishes.
